<p style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-size:16px;line-height:26px;"><span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">空軍においては、</span>'''フライト'''<span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">（flight）が小隊と訳されることがある。これはおおむね3機から6機の航空機によって編成されており、</span>[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%A4%A7%E5%B0%89 大尉]<span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">が</span>[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%8C%87%E6%8F%AE%E5%AE%98 指揮官]<span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">となる。</span></p>

<p style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-size:16px;line-height:26px;"><span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">In an air force context, a "flight" in English is often translated into "小隊" in Japanese. This usually refers to a unit of 3~6 aircrafts, with a captain as its commander.</span></p>

<p style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-size:16px;line-height:26px;margin-bottom:0px!important;"><span style="font-weight:normal;color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15.104px;line-height:24.1664px;">Well, Iwamoto was just a lieutenant, but this should prove "flight" a better translation than "squad". Squad = 小隊 more oftenly happens in a land army context.</span></p><ac_metadata title="Iwamoto/ Iwai equipment translation"> </ac_metadata>